King William School Food and Nutrition
September 5 at 4:08 PM ·

The USDA has extended the summer food waiver through December 31st, 2020. What does this mean? This extension means that King William County Public Schools will now offer FREE breakfast and lunch meals to ALL children 18 and younger through December 31st, 2020. If your student is participating in the 100% virtual learning module or the hybrid (on-site learning) module, please pre-order meals for needed days. Pre-orders can be submitted via the MyPaymentsPlus app or website. Please contact the School Nutrition Office with any questions.

post_text:
Parents of students who attended KWCPS in 2019-2020: Please complete "Returning Student Registration" for your child(ren) if you have not already done so. We ask that this be done by Noon on Monday. Students who have chosen the 100% virtual option will need to have completed this "paperwork" prior to receiving a chromebook. In addition, KWHS students who wish to pick up their schedule on Tuesday will need to have been registered. Parents of rising kindergartners DO NOT need to complete "Returning Student Registration."

If you need to complete this "paperwork", please go the to KWCPS website and click on "Quick Links." Then click on PowerSchool Parent Portal. Once you get into your child's account, click on "Returning Student Registration".

If you have forgotten your login information or have any questions, please contact your child's school.

post_text:
We hope that everyone is safe! We have two updates related to the school reopening:

1) The deadline to submit applications for the 100% Distance Learning Program has been extended until Thursday, August 6th.

2) Since enrollment in the 100% Distance Learning Program directly impacts classroom assignments for those students that are participating in the Alternate Day schedule, there will be a delay in notifying parents of group assignments for those students attending school on alternate days. We are diligently working to get this information to you as quickly as possible.

Please know that staff is doing the best we can to make the school opening work for all students. And we know that parents are also advocating for what is best for their children. With that being said, let's all provide each other some grace.

shared_text:
Hamilton-Holmes
August 3 at 11:13 AM ·

Parents of rising 7th grade students!
A message will be going out later today regarding Pertussis Vaccination Requirements (Tdap) for all students preparing to enter the seventh grade.
If your child has already received this vaccination, please send a copy of the vaccination record to the school.
For those who have not received this vaccination, the Health Department will be providing the immunization at a drive-thru clinic here at HHMS on August 19, 2020 from 9:00-12:00 at no cost to the family/student.
If your child has insurance/FAMIS/Medicaid you will need to bring their insurance card or a copy of the front and back. Also, for the safety of everyone, please wear a mask and remain in your vehicle. Ensure that your child is wearing clothing that allows their arm to be easily accessible.
If you have any questions, please contact the school!

Class of 2020 graduation video announcement!!!! It all came together very quickly last Friday, but we have secured the Diamond (Flying Squirrels) to show the graduation video for the first time with all of us together!! The event will take place on Tuesday, July 28 from 6-8 PM. RSVP to me at cmcconville@kwcps.k12.va.us if you can attend and the name of the 3 guests! Masks will be required until you get to your spot. I will be at the front gate to check you and your 3 guests in! I cannot wait to see all of you!

If you are uncomfortable attending we completely understand and remember all members of the Class of 2020 will receive the graduation video. Go Cavs and Go Squirrels!

The event will take place on Tuesday, July 28 from 6-8 PM. RSVP to me at cmcconville@kwcps.k12.va.us if you can attend and the name of the 3 guests! This will take place of the August 1st celebration as this was the only date available. However, by holding this at the Diamond we can gather together! Masks will be required until you get to your spot. I will be at the front gate to check you and your 3 guests in! I cannot wait to see all of you!

If you are uncomfortable attending we completely understand and remember all members of the Class of 2020 will receive the graduation video. Go Cavs and Go Squirrels!

We are excited to welcome her to our King William County Public School family.

post_text: Welcome Coach Moore!!! 🏈
shared_text:
King William High School
May 10 at 1:54 PM ·

KWHS is excited to announce that Coach Moore is the new leader of our football program! Once a Cavalier always a Cavalier!!!! Go Cavs!

Scott Moore is a 1986 graduate of King William High School, where he was an All-State selection at center for the Cavaliers. As a Cavalier, he lettered in football, baseball, basketball, and track. He continued his football career at the College of William and Mary. Moore earned a B. A. in History from William and Mary and an M.T. from V.C.U. A 26-year veteran of education, Moore has coached and taught in Hanover, West Point, and for the past 18 years at Hermitage High School, where he served as a history teacher and the offensive line coach. He lives in Mechanicsville with his wife, Stephanie. They have two sons Matthew, a law student at the University of Georgia, and Andrew, an engineering major at West Virginia University.

Continuity of learning is important for our students during this difficult time; however, we are ALL feeling overwhelmed by our new "normal". Parents- We KNOW it is a challenging time and we appreciate all that you are doing.

We are excited to share that local public media stations are broadcasting teacher-led classroom instruction that is aligned with the commonwealth’s academic standards into homes. "VA TV Classroom” provides instruction each weekday from 1-3 p.m. to students in grades K-10 who are unable to access other distance learning options due to a lack of high-speed
internet.

Please visit the COVID-19 link on the KWCPS website for additional information.

post_text: KWHS teacher, Mrs. Lohr, has been collecting plastic bags for recycling this year. She has received an update that allows us to submit additional plastic bag weight totals until April 15th. While bags cannot be brought to school, you can weigh them at home (or give your best guess) and email your bag weight totals to tlohr@kwcps.k12.va.us. From there you can take your bags to Food Lion or the dump to be properly recycled. Please try to have all totals submitted by April 13th to give time for submission. We thank you, in advance, for your help this year and Mrs. Lohr should know by April 22nd if KWHS will win the Trex Bench!

post_text:
Yesterday, Gov. Cuomo of New York spoke these words... "I don't even have the words to express my admiration for them. FDR always had words. Courage is not the absence of fear, but rather the assessment that something else is more important than fear. To me that says it all today. Something is more important than their fear, which is their passion, their commitment, for public service, and helping others. That's all it is. It's just their passion and belief in helping others. And that overcomes their fear. And that makes them, in my book, just truly amazing, outstanding human beings."

KWCPS would like to thank medical providers and first responders for their compassion and commitment to our community.

post_text:
Gov. Northam issued Executive Order #53 this past week, and in this order he states, “Unnecessary person-to-person contact increases the risk of transmission and community spread.” He has also prohibited all public and private gatherings of 10 or more individuals.

Therefore, beginning today at 5:00 p.m., all KWCPS buildings and facilities will be closed to the public. This closure includes all school buildings and athletic fields and facilities. Only essential school division personnel will have access to buildings and athletic fields and facilities.

This decision was not an easy one; however, in recent days we have had students and/or community members gather on KWCPS property in groups of up to 30 people. We understand the importance of exercise and socialization for the King William community; however, we feel it is our responsibility to do our part in keeping our community safe and to keep COVID-19 from spreading.

post_text: KWCPS continues to receive guidance from the Virginia Department of Education regarding the state-wide school closure. We are collaborating with school divisions across the Region and the Commonwealth to ensure that we are thoughtful and strategic about our next steps during this unprecedented and challenging period. We would like to ease concerns about two key issues: graduation and promotion to the next grade level. The Virginia Department of Education is looking to waive many of the graduation requirements. Therefore, all seniors who pass required coursework, will receive a King William High School diploma. All students who were on track to advance to the next grade level will be promoted. We encourage families to regularly check the yellow COVID-19 icon on the school division website which provides the most up to date information. Again, we are working diligently on behalf of our students and we thank you for your continued patience.

Staff will be working diligently to provide families with timely updates as we continue to support our school community. We know that there will be many questions, and we ask that you be patient as we work through the next steps. We will post new information on the school division website as it becomes available.

Our hearts are heavy as we realize the importance of schools in our daily lives. We miss our students so very much!

post_text: It is with great sadness that we inform our families that Mrs. Dot Brown, bus driver, passed away on March 22nd. Mrs. Brown served as a bus driver in King William for 41 years. She was a valued member of our school division as she transported our students to and from school each day and she will be missed. Please keep Mrs. Brown’s family in your thoughts and prayers as they go through this difficult time.

If a parent/guardian cannot pick-up meals during the scheduled hours, please contact the School Board office at (804) 769-3434, ext. 0.

post_text:
Please join KWCPS in recognizing, Shabrial Brown, School Social Worker, for all that she does for our students and staff!
(March 1st through 7th is National School Social Work Week.)

School social workers provide a comprehensive approach to meeting the needs of students through early identification, prevention, intervention, counseling, and support to ensure academic success and educational equity for every student. Working collaboratively with school personnel and parents, they reduce or eliminate the social, emotional, economic, and environmental barriers to maximize the potential of all learners.

School social workers are trained to use a wide range of evidence-based, professional strategies to enhance school climate and ensure student success. They are the link between the home, school, and community in providing direct as well as indirect services to students, families, and school personnel. A school social worker addresses a wide range of issues that impede students’ learning, including attendance, truancy, bullying, drug use, and mental health problems.

King William School Food and Nutrition
November 26, 2019 at 11:36 AM ·

King William County Public Schools invites staff, parents, and community members to a meeting about the school wellness policy. The meeting will be held on Monday, December 2, 2019 at 3:30 p.m. in the School Board Office Conference Room. Providing healthy options at school helps keep our children healthy and ready to learn. The school wellness committee helps our District create an action plan for nutrition and physical activity at school. Parents can share their opinions and help make sure the policy is meeting the needs of our students. King William County Public Schools wellness policy can be found on the District website, www.kwcps.k12.va.us by clicking on "School Nutrition" under "Quick Links".

Parents who are unable to attend the meeting can email comments about the wellness policy or nutrition and physical activity at their school to: shharris@kwcps.k12.va.us

We hope you will join us!

post_text:
Our first priority is to provide and maintain a safe and supportive learning environment. We are able to do so because of the support of our students, staff, parents and community.

Last night, the HHMS administrative team received a message that there was rumor of a student making an inappropriate statement in regards to a "shooter coming to Hamilton Holmes". HHMS staff, immediately, notified the School Resource Officer and he, along with the King William Sheriff's Department, began investigating the report last night.

This morning, HHMS staff along with the King William Sheriff's Department completed a thorough investigation and do not believe the threat to be viable. We understand that threats of this nature, cause worry and concern; therefore, we will continue to have additional support from the Sheriff's Department throughout the day and we thank them for their continued support.

post_text: October is Disability History and Awareness Month. Youth with disabilities initiated a campaign in 2009, to have the General Assembly pass a resolution designating October as Disability History and Awareness Month (DHAM). These same youth developed a vision statement for DHAM: Disability history education and awareness will promote positive attitudes in schools creating a culture of mutual respect, understanding, and equal opportunities for all.

King William Cavalier Golf Team
September 23, 2019 at 8:22 PM ·

The King William Cavalier Golf Team are your 2019 2A Regional Champions! Just as they have done all season, the Cavalier Golf team took care of business today at Kiskiack GC. The team shot 326, defeating runner-up Poquoson by 11 strokes. 3rd place Randolph-Henry finished with a 346 followed by Bruton’s 363. Nottoway, Amelia, Prince Edward, and Bluestone finished in places 5-8 respectively.

The Cavs were led by Senior Taylor Hubbard who fired a 6-under 66, good enough to earn Region A Individual Champion. Arria Gross carded an 85 and finished in 10th place overall. Jonah Ibanez shot 87, good enough for 11th place overall. And Michael Knoeller posted an 88 and finished in 12th place overall. The Team is now 22-0 on the season and will now compete in the 2A State Championship at Virginia Tech on October 14. Go Cavs!
text:
Congratulations to the KWHS Golf Team! These young men and women are the 2A Regional Champions! We wish them luck in the state tournament!

post_text: 7th grade GT Seminar classes created science museum-style interactive exhibits as a final project for the year. Students worked in six collaborative teams to learn about different ecosystems, design, build, code, and connect the components. These interactive and informative museum-style displays included robotic creatures and touch-responsive elements corresponding to a slideshow. The teams presented their exhibits to sixth grade science students who evaluated the displays. The Ocean and Rainforest pictured here were voted the favorites! #5Cs
